04305nam a22006495i 9780292772403DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927724037 a10.7560/7681922doi  a(DE-B1597)673210  a(OCoLC)1414455658  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aML3477.8.A97bH66 2015eb 7aART0000002bisacsh04a741.6/742231 aPatoski, Joe Nick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHomegrown :bAustin Music Posters 1967 to 1982 /cNels Jacobson, Joe Nick Patoski; ed. by Alan Schaefer. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2023] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSouthwestern Writers Collection Series, Wittliff Collections at Texas State University00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tIt All Started Here -- tColorful Tales & Early Techniques -- tPosters -- tVULCAN GAS COMPANY -- tBLUES PORTRAITS -- tREIMAGINING TEXAS -- tTRAVELING BANDS -- tPUNK AND THE NEW WAVES -- tLIST OF POSTERS -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBefore Austin became the “live music capital of the world” and attracted tens of thousands of music fans, it had a vibrant local music scene that spanned late sixties psychedelic and avant-garde rock to early eighties punk. Venues such as the Vulcan Gas Company and the Armadillo World Headquarters hosted both innovative local musicians and big-name touring acts. Poster artists not only advertised the performances—they visually defined the music and culture of Austin during this pivotal period. Their posters promoted an alternative lifestyle that permeated the city and reflected Austin’s transformation from a sleepy university town into a veritable oasis of underground artistic and cultural activity in the state of Texas. This book presents a definitive survey of music poster art produced in Austin between 1967 and 1982. It vividly illustrates four distinct generations of posters—psychedelic art of the Vulcan Gas Company, early works from the Armadillo World Headquarters, an emerging variety of styles from the mid-1970s, and the radical visual aesthetic of punk—produced by such renowned artists as Gilbert Shelton, Jim Franklin, Kerry Awn, Micael Priest, Guy Juke, Ken Featherston, NOXX, and Danny Garrett. Setting the posters in context, Texas music and pop-culture authority Joe Nick Patoski details the history of music posters in Austin, and artist and poster art scholar Nels Jacobson explores the lives and techniques of the artists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPopular musiczTexaszAustinxHistory and criticism. 0aPosters, AmericanzTexaszAustiny20th century. 7aART / General.2bisacsh1 aJacobson, Nels, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJacobson, Nels, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatoski, Joe Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaefer, Alan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/76819240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292772403423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292772403/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles